As Maggie wrote to Dr. Math
On 08/16/2004 at 21:47:08 (Eastern Time),
>[Question]
>How do I write 12x^2 + 16x^2 = 4 in the form (x^2/a^2)+(y^2/b^2)=1?
>
>[Difficulty]
>I just do not remember how to do this
>
>[Thoughts]
>I divided the first equation by 4 so that I could make it equal to 
>1...however, i am not sure what to do now 

Thanks for writing to Ask Dr. Math!

Dividing by 4 is a great first step!  That should give you

   3*x^2 + 4*y^2 = 1.

Now recall that a = 1/(1/a) for all nonzero a.  Apply this with
a = 3 and a = 4.  Then finish.

Feel free to reply if I can help further with this question.


